\begin{frame}{Question: Infinitely Many Solutions – System of Equations}
Consider the following system of equations:

\[
\begin{aligned}
mx - 6y &= 10 \\
2x - ny &= 5
\end{aligned}
\]

In the given system, \( m \) and \( n \) are constants.  
The system has \textbf{infinitely many solutions}. What is the value of \( \dfrac{m}{n} \)?

\begin{itemize}
    \item[\textbf{A.}] \( \dfrac{1}{12} \)
    \item[\textbf{B.}] \( \dfrac{1}{3} \)
    \item[\textbf{C.}] \( \dfrac{4}{3} \)
    \item[\textbf{D.}] \( 3 \)
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Answer: System of the Equations}
\small


To compare, write Equation (2) in the form of Equation (1) by multiplying both sides by a constant \( k \):
\[
k(2x - ny) = k \cdot 5 \Rightarrow 2k x - kn y = 5k
\]

Compare with:
\[
mx - 6y = 10
\]

Matching coefficients:
\[
2k = m, \quad kn = 6, \quad 5k = 10 \Rightarrow k = 2
\]

Substitute \( k = 2 \):
\[
m = 2k = 4, \quad n = \frac{6}{k} = 3 \Rightarrow \frac{m}{n} = \frac{4}{3}
\]

\[
\boxed{\text{Correct Answer: C. } \frac{4}{3}}
\]
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Question: No Solution – System of Equations with Fractions}
Consider the system of equations below:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\frac{3}{10}y + \frac{b}{3}x &= \frac{3}{4} - \frac{1}{5}y \\
\frac{3}{8}x + \frac{3}{5} &= -\frac{1}{4}y + \frac{8}{5}
\end{aligned}
\]

In the given system, \( b \) is a constant.  
If the system has \textbf{no solution}, what is the value of \( b \)?
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Answer: No Solution – System of Equations}
\small
\textbf{Step 1: Rewrite both equations in standard form}

\begin{itemize}
    \item First equation:
    \[
    \frac{3}{10}y + \frac{b}{3}x = \frac{3}{4} - \frac{1}{5}y
    \Rightarrow \left( \frac{3}{10} + \frac{1}{5} \right)y + \frac{b}{3}x = \frac{3}{4}
    \Rightarrow \frac{1}{2}y + \frac{b}{3}x = \frac{3}{4}
    \]

    \item Second equation:
    \[
    \frac{3}{8}x + \frac{3}{5} = -\frac{1}{4}y + \frac{8}{5}
    \Rightarrow \frac{3}{8}x + \frac{3}{5} - \frac{8}{5} = -\frac{1}{4}y
    \Rightarrow \frac{3}{8}x - 1 = -\frac{1}{4}y
    \Rightarrow \frac{1}{4}y + \frac{3}{8}x = 1
    \]
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Step 2: Standard forms for comparison}

\[
\text{First: } \frac{b}{3}x + \frac{1}{2}y = \frac{3}{4}
\qquad
\text{Second: } \frac{3}{8}x + \frac{1}{4}y = 1
\]

\textbf{Step 3: No solution requires same slope, different intercepts}

Make slopes equal:
\[
\frac{b}{3} : \frac{1}{2} = \frac{3}{8} : \frac{1}{4}
\Rightarrow \frac{b/3}{1/2} = \frac{3/8}{1/4} \Rightarrow \frac{2b}{3} = \frac{3}{2}
\Rightarrow b = \frac{9}{4}
\]

\textbf{Correct Answer: } \( \boxed{b = \frac{9}{4}} \)
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{System of Equations — Parametric Point }
\textbf{Given:}
\[
3x - 2y = 6 
\]
\[6x - 4y = 12\]

For each real number \( r \), which of the following points lies on the graph of \textbf{each} equation in the \( xy \)-plane?

\begin{itemize}
    \item[\textbf{A.}] \( \left( r, \frac{3r}{2} - 3 \right) \)
    \item[\textbf{B.}] \( \left( \frac{2r - 6}{3}, r \right) \)
    \item[\textbf{C.}] \( \left( r, \frac{3r}{2} - 6 \right) \)
    \item[\textbf{D.}] \( \left( \frac{r - 6}{2}, r \right) \)
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Answer: Parametric Point }
\textbf{Step 1: Note the system of equations}
\[
3x - 2y = 6 \quad \text{and} \quad 6x - 4y = 12
\]
These are equivalent (the second is just the first multiplied by 2), so any point that satisfies one will satisfy the other.

\textbf{Step 2: Check point from Option A:}  
\[
(x, y) = \left( r, \frac{3r}{2} - 3 \right)
\]
Substitute into the first equation:
\[
3r - 2\left( \frac{3r}{2} - 3 \right) = 3r - (3r - 6) = 6
\Rightarrow \text{True!}
\]

So this point lies on both lines for any real \( r \).

\textbf{Correct Answer:} \( \boxed{\textbf{A}} \)
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{System of Equations — Parametric Point }
\textbf{Given:}
\[
4x + y = 10 
\]
\[12x + 3y = 30\]

For each real number \( r \), which of the following points lies on the graph of \textbf{both} equations in the \( xy \)-plane?

\begin{itemize}
    \item[\textbf{A.}] \( \left( r, -4r + 10 \right) \)
    \item[\textbf{B.}] \( \left( \frac{r - 10}{4}, r \right) \)
    \item[\textbf{C.}] \( \left( r, 4r + 10 \right) \)
    \item[\textbf{D.}] \( \left( r, \frac{10 - r}{4} \right) \)
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Answer: Parametric Point }
\textbf{Step 1: Recognize proportional system.}  
The second equation is exactly 3 times the first:
\[
12x + 3y = 3(4x + y) = 30
\]
So any point satisfying the first also satisfies the second — they are the same line.

\textbf{Step 2: Try Option A:}  
\[
(x, y) = \left( r, -4r + 10 \right)
\]
Substitute into the first equation:
\[
4r + (-4r + 10) = 10 \Rightarrow 10 = 10 \quad \text{✓ True!}
\]

\textbf{Correct Answer:} \( \boxed{\textbf{A}} \)
\end{frame}

